In this proclamation, President Barack Obama declares November 2011 as National Alzheimer's Disease Awareness Month. He acknowledges the pain and burden that Alzheimer's disease places on individuals and their families. The proclamation highlights the importance of improving care for Alzheimer's patients, finding new therapies for the disease, and supporting those affected by it. President Obama emphasizes the government's dedication to advancing research on Alzheimer's disease, mentioning the National Alzheimer's Project Act and the establishment of an Advisory Council on Alzheimer's Research, Care, and Services. He also mentions the progress made in identifying genetic markers that may indicate an increased risk of developing Alzheimer's. The proclamation calls for support and understanding for individuals living with Alzheimer's and their caregivers, and it expresses the commitment to work towards a future free of the disease.